[2] Cholera - Ethiopia
Date: Tue 23 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC News [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6290373.stm>

Some 570 people have died in Ethiopia during what aid agencies say is
a cholera outbreak. But Ethiopia's health ministry is resisting
pressure to declare it an emergency, despite evidence that the
epidemic is sweeping the country. Officials are instead describing it
as acute watery diarrhea.
A spokesperson for one aid agency said the government would not
declare it was cholera because of the damage it could cause to the
Ethiopian economy. It could mean that cross-border trade would have
to stop and markets close.
International agencies working in the country say 52 500 people have
been infected with cholera, 1st reported in the southwest last April
2006. "It needs to be declared an emergency because unless it is, the
appropriate measures will not be taken. We need extra resources,"
said an aid worker, who did not want to be named.
The disease has seriously affected Amhara, Tigray, Afar, Oromiya and
the Somali Region.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
