[3] Cholera, diarrhea - Namibia (Kunene)
Date: Tue 23 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The Namibian (Windhoek) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200701230237.html>

Three people have died from cholera in the Kunene Region, where more
than 200 cases of diarrhea and gastroenteritis have been reported
since early December 2006, The Namibian established yesterday, 22 Jan
2007. Another 3 people have died from dehydration resulting from
diarrhea and gastroenteritis, which are caused by dirty water and
poor sanitation.
The Chief Medical Officer of Kunene Region, Dr Ebong Akpabi, said
that the diarrhea outbreak in the region had became a problem and
needed to be addressed "as an emergency," according to the Nampa news
agency. Akpabio was speaking at a Regional Emergency Unit (Remu)
meeting held at Opuwo, Nampa reported.
Yesterday [22 Jan 2007], Dr Norbert Forster, Under Secretary in the
Health Ministry said, "It came from Angola last October [2006], where
cholera is a problem in the Cunene Province of our neighboring
country," Dr Forster told The Namibian. "We only have about one case
(of diarrhea) reported daily now, quite a bit down from 3 or 4 each
day in November and December [2006]," Foster added.
The diarrhea and gastroenteritis outbreak started on 7 Dec 2006, with
a case reported at the border post clinic at Otjimuhaka, which serves
people from Angola and Namibia. It is believed that the disease was
brought into the country by an Angolan citizen who was treated at
Otjimuhaka. The outbreak rapidly spread to other parts of Kunene, and
by 18 Jan 2007, some 229 cases had been reported to the State
hospital at Opuwo.
[Byline: Brigitte Weidlich]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of Namibia showing Opuwo near its northern border with Angola
can be found at:
<http://media.maps.com/magellan/Images/NAMIBI-W1.gif>.
