[4] Cholera - Uganda (Ntungamo, Kampala)
Date: Tue 23 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The Monitor (Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200701221595.html>

An outbreak of cholera in Ntungamo district has left 7 people dead.
27 others have been admitted at Rubaare Health Center and other
private clinics.
District Director of Health Services William Karikwija on Sun 21 Jan
2007 said the epidemic is severe in Rwikiniro, Kayonza and Rubaare
sub-counties. "By Thu 18 Jan 2007, 7 people had died," he said.
Mr Karikwija said they suspect the disease could have been contracted
from someone who had died of the disease in Kampala but was
transported for burial in Ntungamo on 8 Jan 2007. "We suspect the
disease to have originated from a not properly managed funeral of a
cholera case from Kampala," he said. "After a few days, 3 family
members and other people who attended the funeral developed diarrhea."
In Kampala district, a cholera outbreak left more than 10 people dead
and 150 hospitalized. The disease intensified between November and
December 2006 following heavy rains that flooded certain parts of the
city suburbs.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Ntungamo can be found in southwestern Uganda bordering Rwanda,
whereas the capital Kampala area is in the south central part of the
country bordering Lake Victoria. This can be found at:
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/uganda.pdf>.
- Mod.LL]
