[6] Cholera - Kenya (Northeastern Province)
Date: Thu 25 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Shabelle Media Network Somalia [edited]
<http://www.shabelle.net/news/ne2158.htm>

At least 10 people including children and elderly people have
reportedly died from watery diarrhea related diseases in the Somali
inhabited settlements that lie in the Kenyan northeastern provincial
town of Mandhera near the Somali town of Baled Hawo.
Ahmed Omar Salahi, Shabelle reporter in Gedo province, said many
children were sick, as the disease, which doctors in the area have
not declared cholera, could spread into Somalia, where floods and
repeated wars have already had bad impacts on the livelihood of the
pastoral community in southern Somalia.
He said 6 children under the age of 5 were among the dead. Doctors in
Mandhere were endeavoring to treat the sick, urging people to clean
their environment and keep the sanitation of their houses.
Health warnings were also given by medical people in southern Somalia.
[Byline: Aweys Osman Yusuf]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Mandhera (or Mandera) is located at the northeastern tip of Kenya's
Northeastern Province, as seen on the map linked to in the following
posting. The bordering Gedo Province in Somalia can be found at:
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/somalia.pdf>.
- Mod.LL]
