[10] Diarrhea - Philippines (Bohol)
Date: Tue 23 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Sun Star [edited]
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/net/2007/01/24/polluted.water.kills.2.downs.132.in.bohol.html>

A diarrhea outbreak in Loon, Bohol claimed the life of a 3-year-old
girl and caused some 150 residents to be admitted to the provincial
and district hospitals. Health officials are looking at the town's
water source as a possible reason, as the water may be contaminated.
Loon Mayor Cesar Lopez told Sun Star Cebu in a phone interview that
the heavy rains from the latter part of December 2006 to the 1st part
of January 2007 could have caused the contamination.
As of 10:30 a.m. Tue 23 Jan 2007, Department of Health Assistant
Regional Director Lakshmi Legaspi said 112 victims were admitted at
the Loon District Hospital, while there were 4 admissions at the
Gallares Memorial Hospital, a provincial hospital. There were other
victims who were already discharged.
A team from the Regional Epidemiology Surveillance Unit (Resu) in
Central Visayas of the DOH headed by Renan Cimafranca was sent to
take water samples. A team from the DOH-National Epidemiology Center
(Nec) was also at the area. Lopez expects the results Wed 24 Jan 2007.
At least 20 barangays are being served by the water system, but the
victims were from 8 barangays only. DOH Central Visayas, through
Legaspi, is concentrating on 4 barangays -- Basak, Coco-Norte,
Poblacion and Sandingaw Island -- where more victims were noted.
As far as Lopez is concerned, there was no other outbreak this big in
Loon except in 1975, when a cholera outbreak affected the island of Cabilan.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Bohol is an island province of the Philippines located in the
Central Visayas region. To the west of Bohol is Cebu, to the
northeast is the island of Leyte and to the south, across the Bohol
Sea is Mindanao. It can be found on a map at:
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bohol>.
- Mod.LL]
